g reductionistic solutions, and without losing sight of how our lives and those of others are caught up in the moral webs we humans spin, this book skillfully fashions new kinds of conceptual tools from the strange and unexpected properties of the living world itself. In this groundbreaking work, Kohn takes anthropology in a new and exciting direction-one that offers a more capacious way to think about the world we share with other kinds of beings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAguaruna IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aAguaruna mythology. 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxAmazon River Region. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszAmazon River Region. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszEcuador. 0aHuman-plant relationshipsxAmazon River Region. 0aHuman-plant relationshipszAmazon River Region. 0aHuman-plant relationshipszEcuador. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyxAmazon River Region. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyzAmazon River Region. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyzEcuador. 0aPhilosophy of naturexAmazon River Region. 0aPhilosophy of naturezAmazon River Region. 0aQuechua IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aQuechua mythology. 0aSemioticsxAmazon River Region. 0aSemioticszAmazon River Region. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophyxAmazon River RegionxAmazon River RegionxElectronic books. 0aSocial scienceszAmazon River RegionxPhilosophy. 4aamazonian tribe. 4aanimal and plant sentience. 4aanthropologist. 4aanthropology. 4aarborist. 4ado dogs dream. 4aecology. 4aenvironmentalism. 4aenvironmentalist. 4aethnographic. 4aethnography. 4anatural history. 4apolitical activism. 4areductionistic solution. 4aruna of ecuador. 4asocial activist. 4aupper amazon. 4awhat does it mean to be human. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:d